\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and past values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t-1},\varepsilon_{t-2},\ldots,\varepsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
i) What is the difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

? Under which condition on 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}-\sigma_{t}^{2}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 ?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The difference is that 
\begin_inset Formula $_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the process that goes back to the infinite past, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a finite process.
 Consider:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{t}^{2} & =\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\sigma_{t-1}^{2}\\
 & =\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-2}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\sigma_{t-2}^{2}\right)\\
 & =\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-2}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-3}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\sigma_{t-3}^{2}\right)\right)\\
 & =\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-2}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-3}+\gamma\right)^{2}+\beta\sigma_{t-3}^{2}\right)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{t}\equiv\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t}+\gamma\right)^{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{t}^{2} & =\omega+\phi_{t-1}+\beta\left(\omega+\phi_{t-2}+\beta\left(\omega+\phi_{t-3}+\beta\sigma_{t-3}^{2}\right)\right)\\
 & =\omega+\phi_{t-1}+\beta\omega+\beta\phi_{t-2}+\beta^{2}\left(\omega+\phi_{t-3}+\beta\sigma_{t-3}^{2}\right)\\
 & =\omega+\phi_{t-1}+\beta\left(\omega+\phi_{t-2}\right)+\beta^{2}\left(\omega+\phi_{t-3}\right)+\beta^{3}\sigma_{t-3}^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and so on until 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{t}^{2}=\sigma_{0}^{2}\beta^{t}+\sum_{j=0}^{t-1}\beta^{j}\left(\omega+\alpha\left(\varepsilon_{t-j-1}+\gamma\right)^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $_{u}\sigma_{t}^{2}-\sigma_{t}^{2}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, we must have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
